SCAB DISEASE, APPLE - AUSTRALIA: (WESTERN AUSTRALIA), ERADICATION
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon 28 Apr 2008
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) Rural News [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/rural/wa/content/2006/s2229390.htm>


WA officially free of the disease apple scab
--------------------------------------------
Western Australia is now one of the few regions in the world to be
officially free of the disease apple scab. The disease was discovered in a
Perth Hills orchard 3 years ago, and since that time the apple industry has
spend half a million dollars on a state-wide eradication project. Apple
scab leaves blemishes and cracks on apples, which reduces yield and makes
the fruit unsaleable.

Tony Portman, development officer with the Department of Agriculture and
Food, says its eradication project has been laborious but very successful.
"Over 340 000 trees have been inspected. There's over a million trees in
the state. So 30 per cent of the trees have actually been inspected." Mr
Portman says that one of the main bonuses is that growers won't have to
control the disease. "In the Western world most growers lose about 5 per
cent of their crop each year from apple scab."

Angelo Loguidice from WA's Apple and Pear Council says money that has been
spent on eradicating the disease can now be directed towards better
marketing campaigns for apples.

[byline: Skye Shannon]

